Funyula MP Paul Otuoma has ditched ODM following the bungled Busia governor nomination. The lawmaker says the exercise was rigged and has rejected calls to repeat voting. &ldquo;I would like to resign and withdraw my membership with immediate effect,&rdquo; Otuoma said in a letter to the party dated April 20.The MP was an ODM life member and had been issued with a life membership certificate.&ldquo;I have voluntarily opted to leave the party,&rdquo; he said In the letter addressed to ODM secretary general Agnes Zani. The MP said he will run against GovernorSospeter Ojaamong as an independent candidate on August 8. Residents protested after Ojaamong was declared the winner with 92,358 votes against Otuoma&rsquo;s 63,752.Otuoma said his name will be on the ballot paper with or without ODM. &rdquo;I will prepare to run as an independent candidate, if that is the case. That is the only option available given the nominations deadline,&rdquo; he said on Wednesday.&ldquo;I will go to the electorate to ask for votes and let people decide who will be the governor of Busia county. I have already made a decision to quit the Orange party. I am suffering without bitterness,&rdquo; he told the press at Quills Hotel.Otuoma said he still supports party leader Raila Odinga&rsquo;s presidential bid. He said he does not want to involve Raila in the stalemate.The MP said he wants to avoid causing a rift among communities in Busia, as the Teso and Luhya have lived peacefully for many years.